    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-01-15T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-01-15T01:00:00-05:00" n="821"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d821">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/15232: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-15T13:00:00+07:00"
                            >January 15, 1944—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 17—12:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>98. We are taking up vigorously with Chinese Government subject of our 97,
                    January 15, by formal note to Foreign Office and as soon <pb facs="1113"
                        n="1099" xml:id="pg_1099"/> as it can be arranged personal interview with
                        Soong,<note n="5" xml:id="d821fn5">T. V. Soong, Chinese Minister for Foreign
                        Affairs.</note> and Kunming [is] being instructed to avoid publicity and
                    report fully [and] promptly developments; to telegraph in confidential code,
                    repeating telegrams to Department.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
